<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-472-686  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 472 686.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 31 1989 v6 n30 p23(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users of Word 5.0 encounter glitch in importing documents.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Picarille, Lisa.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Users are complaining that Microsoft Word 5.0 is defective whenused to import documents from Word 4.0.andP;  Version 5.0 does notrecognize the length of the document being imported and so failsto save the entire document.andP;  One corporate user claims that helost two-thirds of a 15-page Word 4.0 document when it was beingimported to Word 5.0.andP;  Microsoft investigated the complaints andfound a bug in 4.0's spelling checker.andP;  Because the formatting ofdocuments that have been put through the spelling checker arecorrupted or slightly altered, Word 5.0 is unable to read them.andO;The company plans to issue a disk that will give 5.0 the abilityto read corrupted 4.0 files.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product enhancement).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Word 5.0 (Word processing software) (productenhancement)Microsoft Word 4.0 (Word processing software) (defects).andO;Topic:     DefectsEnhancementsWord processing softwareSoftware Migration.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Lisa PicarilleandM;A handful of users of Microsoft Corp.'s Word program have reportedencountering idiosyncrasies when bringing files created in version 4.0 of theword processor into version 5.0.andM;Word 5.0 apparently doesn't recognize the length of documents imported fromthe previous release of the product and, as a result, fails to save theentire document, according to corporate users who have experienced theproblem.andM;&quot;I lost two-thirds of a 15-page Word 4.0 document when I tried to import itinto 5.0,&quot; said one Word 5.0 user, an engineer at a large electronicsmanufacturing firm in Baltimore who asked not be identified.andM;Microsoft officials confirmed that the problem can occur, explaining that thebug is in Word 4.0, not 5.0, which the company released in April at Comdex/Spring.andM;&quot;This is something that we found late in Word 4.0,&quot; said Melinda French, theproduct manager for Word 5.0 at Microsoft, in Redmond, Wash.andM;After tracking several complaints from users about incompatibilities betweenWord 4.0 and 5.0 files, Microsoft has narrowed down the problem to a bug in4.0's spelling checker, according to French.andM;In random cases, Word 4.0 can corrupt or slightly alter the formatting of thedocuments that have been put through the application's spelling checker, sheexplained.andM;&quot;In some cases, users may not even notice the funny formatting,&quot; French said.andO;&quot;But when these corrupted documents are brought into 5.0, the program isn'tcapable of reading the files.&quot;andM;Microsoft plans to issue a fix for the problem, according to French.andP;  Theforthcoming solution may be in the form of a disk that would give Word 5.0the ability to read in corrupted 4.0 files, she said, adding that the companyhas not decided when to release the fix.andM;In the meantime, Microsoft is offering users a work-around solution to theproblem.andP;  Users should save Word 4.0 files within version 4.0 using theprogram's RTF option, according to French.andP;  The option translates the 4.0files into ASCII files, which can then be brought into version 5.0, she said.andM;Once the 4.0 file is imported into 5.0, the user reattaches the style sheet,and the file is automatically converted to a Word 5.0 format, Frenchexplained.andO;</TEXT></DOC>